Pandas user-defined functions — vectorized through Apache Arrow.

If you must run Python, this is the fast way to do it. A pandas user-defined function, also called a vectorized function, does not ship data row by row. Instead it moves whole columns in batches using Apache Arrow's columnar format. Inside the function you receive a pandas series, not a single value, and you operate on the whole batch at once with numpy and pandas vectorization.

The win is twofold. Arrow eliminates almost all of the serialization cost that crippled the plain Python function, and the vectorized math inside processes a batch in one shot instead of one element at a time. The result is dramatically faster while still letting you write ordinary pandas code.

There are three flavors worth knowing. The default is series to series — a pandas series comes in, a pandas series goes out, and this covers most row-wise transformations. The iterator flavor takes an iterator of series, which lets you do expensive setup once — load a model, open a database connection — before processing the batches that follow. And apply-in-pandas works on a whole group at a time, handing your function a complete pandas dataframe per group, which is what you need for custom group aggregations like a median that no built-in provides.

So the order of preference becomes clear. Built-ins first, then higher-order functions, and when you truly need Python, a pandas user-defined function before ever a plain one.
